values.name: useNodes
values.description: Focused hook. Subscribes via adapter.subscribeToNodes(). Returns nodes, setNodes, updateNode. suppressUpdates ref prevents loops during drag.

values.name: computePresentation

values.name: yjsAdapter

values.name: Y.Doc
values.description: Yjs document. ydoc.transact() for mutations, observeDeep() for change notification. Origin tags: 'drag-commit', 'server', 'user'.

values.name: doc-operations
values.description: Shared Y.Doc mutation functions. createConstruct, connect, batchMutate. Used by both yjsAdapter (client) and document-server-core (server). All ops wrapped in ydoc.transact().

values.name: WebSocket

values.name: document-server-core
values.description: HTTP request handler. handleHttpRequest() routes REST calls. Imports from @carta/document. Broadcasts Y.Doc updates via WebSocket.

pages.name: Demo
pages.description: Documents what the Carta demo entails across four stages, so AI can read the compiled output and verify that other levels support it.

values.name: Powerful Modeling Tool
values.narrative: Carta is not a drawing tool â€” it's a modeling tool. Users define their own types (schemas) and define what connections mean between them. You can model anything: frontend components, backend services, serverless functions, user stories, or even sentences. It supports real-time collaboration and web hosting, making it both a product-building tool and a living source of truth.
values.keyInsight: Unlike Excalidraw or Miro, Carta models have semantic meaning. Types and connections carry information, not just shapes and arrows.

values.name: AI Code Generation
values.narrative: Because types carry semantic information, users can export their models as structured JSON. An AI agent with access to this output can generate a complete product in any stack â€” e.g., define API endpoints, request models, and database tables, then let an agent scaffold the whole thing in Fastify/Prisma/Postgres or any other stack.
values.keyInsight: AI agents create great code when they have great instructions. Carta turns visual models into machine-readable specs.

values.name: AI Import via MCP
values.narrative: The flow works in reverse too. Thanks to MCP support, an AI agent can read existing code and create types and instances inside Carta. Users can import a legacy API to make sense of it, or let their AI agent continuously update the model as code evolves.
values.keyInsight: Carta isn't just an input to AI â€” AI can write back into Carta. The model becomes a two-way bridge between human understanding and code.

values.name: The Vision
values.narrative: Human, source of truth, and code interoperate at the speed of AI. Code becomes completely faithful to the product it implements. Code refactorings only happen when there is a product refactoring before it. AI is like the assembly line â€” we won't realize its full potential until we move everyone to work around it. Instead of speeding up isolated parts of existing processes, we speed up the entire product development lifecycle with workflows tailored for AI.
values.keyInsight: Carta unleashes the full potential of AI by putting a semantic source of truth at the center of the development process.

values.name: Custom Types
values.demonstrates: Users create their own construct schemas with typed fields, not generic shapes
values.howShown: Create a schema for 'API Endpoint' with fields like method, path, description

values.name: Semantic Connections
values.demonstrates: Connections between types have meaning â€” ports define what can connect to what and why
values.howShown: Connect an API Endpoint to a Database Table via a 'reads from' port, show that random types can't connect arbitrarily

values.name: Model Anything
values.demonstrates: Carta is domain-agnostic â€” the same tool models frontend, backend, serverless, user stories, or brainstorming
values.howShown: Show multiple schema groups: software architecture, capability model, or a custom domain the user invented

values.name: Collaboration & Hosting
values.demonstrates: Real-time collaboration and web hosting make Carta a living source of truth, not a static diagram
values.howShown: Show two cursors editing the same document, or show accessing a hosted document via URL

values.name: Semantic Export
values.demonstrates: Models compile to structured, AI-readable JSON output with all semantic information preserved
values.howShown: Click compile, show the JSON output with types, instances, connections, and semantic descriptions

values.name: AI Generates Product
values.demonstrates: An AI agent reads the compiled output and generates a complete working product in any stack
values.howShown: Feed the compiled JSON to an AI agent, it generates Fastify routes, Prisma schema, and Postgres migrations matching the model exactly

values.name: Any Stack
values.demonstrates: The same model can target different tech stacks â€” the model is stack-agnostic
values.howShown: Show the same API model generating code for Fastify/Prisma and then for Express/Sequelize or Django

values.name: Import Existing Code
values.demonstrates: AI can read existing codebases and create Carta types and instances from them
values.howShown: Point an AI agent at a legacy API, it creates schemas and populates instances in Carta representing what it found

values.name: AI Updates Model
values.demonstrates: AI agents can continuously update the Carta model as code evolves via MCP
values.howShown: Show an AI agent adding a new endpoint construct after detecting a new route in the codebase

values.name: Two-Way Bridge
values.demonstrates: Carta is both readable and writable by AI â€” the model is a live bridge, not a one-time export
values.howShown: Show the round-trip: model â†’ code â†’ model update, demonstrating the feedback loop

values.name: Product-First Development
values.demonstrates: Code refactorings only happen when there's a product refactoring first â€” the model drives the code, not the reverse
values.howShown: Show changing the model (e.g., splitting an endpoint), then having AI update the code to match

values.name: Assembly Line Analogy
values.demonstrates: AI is like the assembly line â€” its full potential requires reorganizing workflows around it, not bolting it onto existing ones
values.howShown: Contrast: AI as autocomplete in an IDE vs. AI as the execution layer in a model-driven workflow

values.name: Models carry meaning, not just shapes
values.evidence: Custom types with typed fields and semantic connections prove this isn't a drawing tool â€” it's a knowledge tool

values.name: Great instructions produce great code
values.evidence: Semantic export gives AI agents structured, typed specs â€” not vague descriptions. The output quality is bounded by the input quality.

values.name: The model is a two-way bridge
values.evidence: MCP support means AI can both read and write the model. It's not a one-time export â€” it's a living feedback loop between human intent and code.

values.name: Carta unleashes the full potential of AI
values.evidence: AI's impact requires reorganizing workflows around it. Carta puts a semantic source of truth at the center, enabling product-first development where code is always faithful to the model.

values.name: This Is a Carta Document
values.demonstrates: The demo itself is a real Carta document modeling Carta. The levels (Product, Architecture, Demo) are visible â€” the tool is modeling itself.
values.howShown: Casually reveal the document's level tabs. Show that the demo you're presenting from is itself a Carta document with multiple levels describing the product.

values.name: Real Specs, Not Hypothetical
values.demonstrates: The compiled output isn't a toy example â€” it's the actual specs AI agents consume when working on Carta's codebase.
values.howShown: Show the compiled output of the Carta-describes-Carta document and note that this is what feeds into real development sessions.

values.name: Self-Building Dev Loop
values.demonstrates: Carta is built using Carta. The development loop: update the model, encounter a limitation or feature idea, queue a plan for another AI agent, continue. The model, the code, and the developer co-evolve.
values.howShown: Walk through the actual dev loop: show the Carta document levels, show a queued todo-plan, show an AI agent picking it up. The product builds itself.

pages.name: Dev Workflow
pages.description: How the AI-assisted development loop works: carta-builder models the product, discovers issues, creates todo-tasks; implementor grooms and executes them; verification feeds back.

data.name: Loop 1: Modeling & Discovery
data.description: carta-builder reads code, models in Carta document, discovers issues and gaps while modeling. Outputs todo-tasks.

data.name: Loop 2: Grooming & Execution
data.description: carta-feature-implementor picks up todo-tasks, grooms into implementation-ready plans, launches headless agents, verifies results.

values.name: Start session
values.description: User invokes /carta-builder

values.name: Read codebase
values.description: Read .docs/MANIFEST.md, source files, existing Carta document. Orient on both sides.

values.name: Model in Carta
values.description: Create/update constructs, connections, organizers. Reify code structure into diagram.

values.name: Issue found?
values.description: Does modeling reveal a gap, bug, missing feature, or friction?

values.name: Write todo-task
values.description: Write motivation, scope, design direction to todo-tasks/*.md. Frontload summary in first 10 lines.

values.name: Compile & reflect
values.description: Compile document, check if output is useful to AI. Surface friction between diagram and code.

values.name: Pick up task
values.description: /carta-feature-implementor lists todo-tasks/, checks running agents, selects a plan to groom.

values.name: Groom plan
values.description: Read code context, brief user, resolve design decisions, add Do NOT section, concrete file refs, plan-specific checks.

values.name: Execute in worktree
values.description: /execute-plan launches headless Sonnet in a git worktree. Agent echoes constraints, implements step-by-step, commits incrementally.

values.name: Build & test pass?
values.description: pnpm build && pnpm test + plan-specific grep checks

values.name: Fix violations
values.description: Agent fixes build/test failures or plan constraint violations. Runs verify-against-plan checklist.

values.name: Merge to trunk
values.description: On success, worktree branch merges into trunk. Plan archived to todo-tasks/.archived/.

values.name: Debrief
values.description: Compare agent output to plan intent. Feed learnings back into skill/agent configs.

values.name: todo-tasks/*.md
values.description: Plan files with motivation, scope, design direction. Written by carta-builder, consumed by implementor.

values.name: Groomed plan
values.description: Refined plan with Do NOT section, concrete file refs, plan-specific checks. Unambiguous enough for headless agent.

values.name: Agent configs
values.description: plan-executor.md, SKILL.md files. Updated via debrief when agent drift is detected.

data.name: Loop 3: Headless Execution (in worktree)
data.description: What the plan-executor agent does autonomously inside a git worktree. Reads plan, echoes constraints, implements, verifies, commits.

values.name: Agent starts
values.description: execute-plan.sh creates worktree, installs deps, launches claude -p with plan prompt

values.name: Read plan & echo constraints
values.description: Read todo-tasks/*.md. List back Do NOT items, Design constraint, Out of Scope. This is the guardrail checklist.

values.name: Orient
values.description: Read .docs/MANIFEST.md, relevant docs, existing source files that will be modified. Understand before changing.

values.name: Implement step-by-step
values.description: Work through plan steps in order. Commit after each logical unit. Stage specific files, not git add -A.

values.name: Verify against plan
values.description: Review changes against constraint checklist. Confirm no files outside Files to Modify touched, no Do NOT violations, no scope creep.

values.name: Run plan-specific checks
values.description: Execute grep-based assertions from plan. E.g., ! grep -q 'isEditingDescription' to verify removed code stays gone.

values.name: pnpm build && test?
values.description: Run pnpm build && pnpm test (NOT test:e2e). Fix failures before finishing.

values.name: Done
values.description: Output summary: commits, files changed, build/test status, deviations from plan.

data.name: Example: Directional Auto-Layout â€” Discovery
data.description: While modeling the Architecture page, carta-builder noticed the existing spread/compact layouts ignore edge direction. This matters for flow diagrams. Wrote todo-task.

data.name: Example: Directional Auto-Layout â€” Grooming
data.description: Implementor read the task, explored spreadNodes.ts and Map.tsx, resolved decisions (TB only, top-level nodes only, Sugiyama algorithm), refined into step-by-step plan.

data.name: Example: Directional Auto-Layout â€” Execution
data.description: Headless Sonnet agent created hierarchicalLayout.ts (267 lines), added toolbar button to Map.tsx, passed build+test. One commit: 9ded784.

values.name: Model Architecture page
values.description: carta-builder reading packages, creating Module constructs, connecting them with flow edges to show data dependencies.

values.name: Try layout tools
values.description: Used spread and compact layout on the Architecture page. Nodes went into a grid â€” edge direction was lost. Sources and sinks ended up side-by-side.

values.name: Identify gap
values.description: Existing layouts (spreadNodes, compactNodes) are grid-based. No algorithm considers edge topology. Users modeling data flow or dependency chains need directional layout.

values.name: Write todo-task
values.description: Created directional-auto-layout.md: scope = new feature, 1 new file + 1 modified, summary of Sugiyama approach. Frontloaded summary in first 10 lines.

values.name: Read task + explore code
values.description: Read directional-auto-layout.md. Explored spreadNodes.ts (existing pattern), compactNodes.ts, Map.tsx toolbar section. Understood SpreadInput type.

values.name: Resolve decisions
values.description: TB-only (not LR). Top-level nodes only (organizers treated as single nodes). DFS cycle-breaking. Reuse SpreadInput type. Centroid preservation required.

values.name: Refine plan
values.description: Rewrote plan with: exact function signature, algorithm steps 1-7, Map.tsx callback code, toolbar button SVG, file locations with line numbers.

values.name: Launch agent
values.description: execute-plan.sh directional-auto-layout â†’ created worktree carta-agent-directional-auto-layout, installed deps, launched claude -p.

values.name: Read plan, echo constraints
values.description: Agent listed: TB only, top-level only, reuse SpreadInput, centroid preservation required, pure function (no React deps).

values.name: Create hierarchicalLayout.ts
values.description: 267 lines. Built adjacency, DFS cycle-breaking, longest-path layer assignment, barycenter ordering, coordinate assignment, centroid shift.

values.name: Add toolbar button to Map.tsx
values.description: Added handleHierarchicalLayout callback (same pattern as handleCompactAll), tree-shaped SVG icon in ControlButton.

values.name: Build+test pass
values.description: pnpm build âœ“, 212 web-client tests âœ“, 13 server tests âœ“. Commit 9ded784. Merged to trunk.

values.name: directional-auto-layout.md
values.description: Scope: new feature, 1 new + 1 modified. Sugiyama-style TB layout. Motivation: spread/compact ignore edges.

values.name: Groomed plan
values.description: Exact function sig, SpreadInput reuse, 7 algorithm steps, Map.tsx callback code, toolbar SVG, line number refs.
